omkring 1275","ABT    1305":"omkring 1305","Wales":"Wales","Merionethshire, Wales":"Merionethshire, Wales"},"nl":{"about 1275–after 1305":"circa 1275–na 1305","1275–1305":"1275–1305","1305–Male":"1305–Overleden","1330–Male":"1330–Overleden","1240–1275":"1240–1275","1239–Female":"1239–Overleden","1239":"1239","1305":"1305","after 1305":"na 1305","1330":"1330","1275":"1275","1240":"1240","after 1275":"na 1275","about 1275":"circa 1275","ABT    1305":"circa 1305","Wales":"Wales","Merionethshire, Wales":"Merionethshire, Wales"},"en":{"about 1275–after 1305":"about 1275–after 1305","1275–1305":"1275–1305","1305–Male":"1305–Deceased","1330–Male":"1330–Deceased","1240–1275":"1240–1275","1239–Female":"1239–Deceased","1239":"1239","1305":"1305","after 1305":"after 1305","1330":"1330","1275":"1275","1240":"1240","after 1275":"after 1275","about 1275":"about 1275","ABT    1305":"about 1305","Wales":"Wales","Merionethshire, Wales":"Merionethshire, Wales","nameMeanings":[{"name":"ap","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Vietnamese Hung, Long, Minh, Muoi, Phan, Phat, Vinh, Cuong, Hien, Hoa, Lam, Lan.  Chinese Wing, Chi, Kin, Cheuk, Chi Wai, Chuen, Hon, Keung, Wah, Wai, Chiu, Ho.","Chinese: alternative Mandarin form of the surname 敖, see   Ao  .","Chinese: Cantonese form of the surnames 歐 and 區, see   Ou   1 and 2."],"variants":[{"name":"Auerbach","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Hyman, Moshe, Emanuel, Isidor, Bronia, Chaim, Faigy, Menachem, Meyer, Yechezkel.","German: habitational name from any of several places in southern Germany and Austria called Auerbach ‘the stream at the water meadow’. See also 2,   Au  , and   Bach  .","Jewish (Ashkenazic): habitational name from the town of Auerbach in the Upper Palatinate, Bavaria. Compare   Averbach  ."]},{"name":"Ao","meanings":["Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 敖, meaning both ‘rambling’ and ‘deposed king without posthumous titles’ in ancient Chinese: (i) from the personal name of <i>Tai Ao</i> (太敖), teacher of the legendary king Zhuanxu (traditional dates: 2514–2437  BC ). (ii) it is said that the surname is also borne by descendants of deposed kings of the former state of Chu, with no posthumous titles, during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC )."]},{"name":"Auer","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Alois, Hans, Erwin, Matthias, Siegfried, Bernd, Bernhard, Erna, Franz, Fritz, Hermann, Horst.","German (mainly Bavaria): topographic name for someone living by a water meadow, German <i>Au</i>, or a habitational name for someone from a place called Au or Aue (see   Au   and   Aue  ). This surname is also found in France (Alsace and Lorraine), Czechia, and Slovenia."]}]},{"name":"Tudyr","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Welsh: from the personal name <i>Tudur</i>, a derivative of British Celtic <i>Toutorīx</i>, literally ‘people’ + ‘king’. It has sometimes been taken as a Welsh equivalent of Latin <i>Theodorus</i>, from Greek <i>Theodōros</i> ‘gift of God’ (see   Theodore  ), for which the usual Welsh form is <i>Tewdwr</i>.","Romanian and Croatian: from the personal name <i>Tudor</i>, a variant of <i>Teodor</i> (see   Theodore  ).","History: The Tudor royal family, English sovereigns from the accession of Henry VII in 1485 to the death of Elizabeth I in 1603, were of Welsh origin, being descended from Owain ap Maredudd ap Tudur, who held lands at Penmynydd in Anglesey."],"variants":[{"name":"Tutor","meanings":["Probably Welsh: variant of   Tudor  ."]},{"name":"Theodore","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French/Haitian Serge, Henri, Pierre, Alide, Andre, Antoine, Benoit, Berthony, Chantal, Daphnee, Edouard, Guilene.","French and Mauritian (<b>Théodore</b>); West Indian (in Haiti, Martinique, and Guadeloupe <b>Théodore</b>); English and Welsh: from a personal name derived from Greek <i>Theodōros</i>, a compound of <i>theos</i> ‘God’ + <i>dōron</i> ‘gift’, which was relatively popular in the Middle Ages because of its auspicious meaning. The name was borne by several early Christian saints. There was considerable confusion with the ancient Germanic name <i>Theodoric</i> (see   Terry  ). In Wales, the personal name <i>Theodore</i> was also adopted as an approximation to the Welsh name <i>Tewdwr</i> (see   Tudor  ). In North America, this surname has absorbed various other European cognates and their derivatives, e.g. Greek   Theodorakis  , Macedonian <b>Todorovski</b>, and Serbian <b>Todorović</b> (see   Todorovic  )."]},{"name":"Tedder","meanings":["English (Surrey): from the Middle English personal name <i>Thedere</i>, <i>Teddere</i>, which is either from the Old English personal name <i>Thēodhere</i> (from <i>thēod</i> ‘people’ + <i>here</i> ‘army’) or from the cognate ancient Germanic personal name <i>Theudher</i>, which seems to have been adopted by the Normans. Alternatively, perhaps it may be an occupational name from Middle English <i>teddere</i> ‘one who teds’, i.e. a person whose occupation was to spread mown grass for drying.","Welsh: variant of   Tudor  ."]}]},{"name":"Llywelyn","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["(Welsh)  See  Llewelyn ."],"variants":[{"name":"Llewelyn","meanings":["Traditional: altered form (influenced by <i>llew</i> ‘lion’) of <i>Llywelyn</i>, an ancient name of uncertain derivation. It probably goes back to the Old Celtic name <i>Lugobelinos</i>, the first element of which is <i>Lugu-</i> (the name of a god;  see  Lleu  ); the second is a name-forming element found also in names such as <i>Cunobelinus</i> (<i>Cymbeline</i>). The name was borne by  Llywelyn ap Iorwerth  (  1173–1240 ) and his grandson Llywelyn ap Gruffydd (  d. 1282 ), Welsh princes who for a time united their countrymen in North Wales and led opposition to the power of the Norman barons in South Wales and the Marches."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Llywelyn ap Tudyr of Mathavarn was born about 1275, in Merionethshire, Wales, his father, Tudyr ap Gronwy of Mathrafarn, was 37 and his mother, Margaret Verch Llywelyn, was 37. He had at least 2 sons with Gwenllian ferch Llywelyn. He died after 1305, in Wales."},"et":{"about 1275–after 1305":"umbes 1275–pärast 1305","1275–1305":"1275–1305","1305–Male":"1305–Surnud","1330–Male":"1330–Surnud","1240–1275":"1240–1275","1239–Female":"1239–Surnud","1239":"1239","1305":"1305","after 1305":"pärast 1305","1330":"1330","1275":"1275","1240":"1240","after 1275":"pärast 1275","about 1275":"umbes 1275","ABT    1305":"umbes 1305","Wales":"Wales","Merionethshire, Wales":"Merionethshire, Wales"},"fi":{"about 1275–after 1305":"noin 1275–1305 jälkeen","1275–1305":"1275–1305","1305–Male":"1305–Kuollut","1330–Male":"1330–Kuollut","1240–1275":"1240–1275","1239–Female":"1239–Kuollut","1239":"1239","1305":"1305","after 1305":"1305 jälkeen","1330":"1330","1275":"1275","1240":"1240","after 1275":"1275 jälkeen","about 1275":"noin 1275","ABT    1305":"noin 1305","Wales":"Wales","Merionethshire, Wales":"Merionethshire, Wales"},"fr":{"about 1275–after 1305":"environ 1275–après 1305","1275–1305":"1275–1305","1305–Male":"1305–Décédé","1330–Male":"1330–Décédé","1240–1275":"1240–1275","1239–Female":"1239–Décédée","1239":"1239","1305":"1305","after 1305":"après 1305","1330":"1330","1275":"1275","1240":"1240","after 1275":"après 1275","about 1275":"environ 1275","ABT    1305":"environ 1305","Wales":"Galles","Merionethshire, Wales":"Merionethshire, Galles","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Llywelyn ap Tudyr of Mathavarn est né environ 1275, à Merionethshire, Galles, son père, Tudyr ap Gronwy of Mathrafarn, avait 37 ans et sa mère, Margaret Verch Llywelyn, avait 37 ans. Il a eu au moins 2 fils avec Gwenllian ferch Llywelyn. Il est décédé après 1305, à Galles."},"de":{"about 1275–after 1305":"um 1275–nach 1305","1275–1305